If an Exception is thrown with a file value over 255 characters in length, the log record is not displayed in www.larabug.com

I expect this doesn't happen often with file paths, however, in cases where the Exception is thrown from a chunky route closure, this can crop up more readily.

Example route closure:

```php
Route::get('testErrorLog', function () {
  $channel = request()->get('channel');
  $e = new \Exception('This is a test error log message');

  if (array_key_exists($channel, config('logging.channels'))) {
    logger()->channel($channel)->error('test', ['exception' => $e]);
    return sprintf('Logged test error to %s', $channel);
  }

  throw $e;
});
```
The Larabug client sends a file value that looks something like this:

```json
{
        "file": "laravel-serializable-closure:\/\/function () {\n          $channel = request()->get('channel');\n          $e = new \\Exception('This is a test error log message');\n\n          if (array_key_exists($channel, config('logging.channels'))) {\n            logger()->channel($channel)->error('test', ['exception' => $e]);\n            return sprintf('Logged test error to %s', $channel);\n          }\n\n          throw $e;\n        }",
}
```
Well over 255 characters.

In such cases, the request to log the Exception in www.larabug.com succeeds and a log id is returned, but the log record does not appear to be visible in the web UI. Navigating to the record via:

https://www.larabug.com/panel/projects/[PROJECT_KEY]/exceptions/[LOG_ID]

also does not display the record.

I grant that this is a niche case, but in case anyone else stumbles across this, it could save them a bit of head-scratching.
